on-qvc-is-it-going-to-pot","type":"article","sectionId":"lifeandstyle","sectionName":"Life and style","webPublicationDate":"2016-09-13T13:56:20Z","webTitle":"Le Creuset starts selling on QVC. Is it going to pot?","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/shortcuts/2016/sep/13/le-creuset-starts-selling-on-qvc-is-it-going-to-pot","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/lifeandstyle/shortcuts/2016/sep/13/le-creuset-starts-selling-on-qvc-is-it-going-to-pot","fields":{"headline":"Le Creuset starts selling on QVC. Is it going to pot?","standfirst":"<p>The pricey French pan-maker has made a play for the mass market by offering discounts on the shopping channel</p>","trailText":"The pricey French pan-maker has made a play for the mass market by offering discounts on the shopping channel","main":"<figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"a7efe31f9c08555892029355395f9c4aca3df247\"> <img src=\"https://media.guim.co.uk/a7efe31f9c08555892029355395f9c4aca3df247/801_784_4195_2517/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Le Creuset ... how’s that move panning out?\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Le Creuset ... how’s that move panning out?</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Katherine Anne Rose for the Observer</span> </figcaption> </figure>","body":"<p><strong>Name:</strong> Le Creuset.</p> <p><strong>Age:</strong> 91.</p> <p><strong>Pots and pans, aren’t they?</strong> Indeed, but not just any pots and pans. These pride themselves on being top of the range.</p> <p><strong>French?</strong> You are on fire today. Le Creuset means “the cauldron”, and the company was founded <a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/world/gallery/2015/sep/07/le-creuset-celebrates-90-years-in-pictures\" title=\"\">in Fresnoy-le-Grand, northern France, in 1925</a>, producing cocottes.</p> <p><strong>I thought cocotte meant “floozie”?</strong> I see your time studying French at school was not entirely wasted. It does, but it also means a fireproof dish in which food is cooked or served. Le Creuset’s “French ovens” were a huge success and by the 1980s were gracing middle-class dinner tables all over Europe.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/world/gallery/2015/sep/07/le-creuset-celebrates-90-years-in-pictures\">Le Creuset celebrates 90 years - in pictures</a> </p> </aside>  <p><strong>Orange, I seem to recall.</strong> Volcanic orange – representing the heat of the foundry in which they are made – is the most famous colour, but you can also get them in almond, amethyst, burgundy, cassis, cerise, chiffon pink, ink, kiwi, Marseille blue, nutmeg, satin black ...</p> <p><strong>OK, I get the picture. It’s a famous brand that has branched out. </strong>And it is the branching out that may be the problem.</p> <p><strong>How come?</strong> In what has been interpreted as a move into the mass market, Le Creuset is <a href=\"http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/09/13/le-creuset-no-longer-a-preserve-of-middle-class-kitchens-as-it-t/\" title=\"\">allowing its products to be sold at a discount on the shopping channel QVC</a>.</p> <p><strong>Sacré bleu! </strong>More sacré orange, but yes, your surprise is shared by marketing experts, who worry that price-cutting will “pollute the brand”. Owning Le Creuset was a statement of your middle-class credentials. If everyone has them, well ...</p> <p><strong>I take it you live in Notting Hill?</strong> Naturally.</p> <p><strong>So what is the poor middle-class Le Creuset owner to do?</strong> They could always switch to cookware made by <a href=\"http://www.jodyeddy.com/site/2011/05/31/e-dehillerin-the-19th-century-parisian-cookware-store-where-julia-child-was-a-regular/comment-page-1/\" title=\"\">Paris-based E Dehillerin</a>. They really are exclusive.</p> <p><strong>Pricey?</strong> Darling, one doesn’t ask.</p> <p><strong>Isn’t there some story about Jeanette Winterson and Le Creuset? </strong>You really are determined to take this downmarket, aren’t you? There was a tale that, in her younger days, ladies in Chelsea paid <a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/books/2000/sep/02/fiction.jeanettewinterson\" title=\"\">Winterson for sexual favours by buying her Le Creuset pans</a>, but it may have been overcooked.</p> <p><strong>A brief note on pronunciation:</strong> It’s Luh Cru-Zay, not Ler Crew-Zay or Ler Crew-Set. Possibly.</p> <p><strong>Do say:</strong> “Reassuringly expensive.”</p> <p><strong>Don’t say: </strong>“Forty percent off.”</p>","newspaperPageNumber":"3","wordcount":"367","commentCloseDate":"2016-09-16T13:00:00Z","commentable":"true","creationDate":"2016-09-13T11:28:23Z","firstPublicationDate":"2016-09-13T13:56:20Z","internalComposerCode":"57d7e2d7e4b08465d45002d7","internalOctopusCode":"11897505","internalPageCode":"2714737","isInappropriateForSponsorship":"false","isPremoderated":"false","lastModified":"2016-09-15T16:33:46Z","newspaperEditionDate":"2016-09-14T00:00:00Z","productionOffice":"UK","publication":"The Guardian","shortUrl":"https://gu.com/p/52zzm","shouldHideAdverts":"false","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"https://media.guim.co.uk/a7efe31f9c08555892029355395f9c4aca3df247/801_784_4195_2517/500.jpg","legallySensitive":"false","lang":"en","internalRevision":"49","internalShortId":"/p/52zzm"},"tags":[{"id":"lifeandstyle/food-and-drink","type":"keyword","sectionId":"lifeandstyle","sectionName":"Life and style","webTitle":"Food & drink","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/food-and-drink","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/lifeandstyle/food-and-drink","references":[]},{"id":"tone/features","type":"tone","webTitle":"Features","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/tone/features","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/tone/features","references":[]},{"id":"news/series/pass-notes","type":"series","sectionId":"news","sectionName":"News","webTitle":"Pass notes","webUrl":"https:/