ong>Name:</strong> Bring-backery.</p> <p><strong>Age:</strong> From the old days, when things were bad and people were stupid.</p> <p><strong>Appearance: </strong>Awful.</p> <p><strong>I’ve heard a lot about this lately.</strong> Of course you have. It’s because of <a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/education/2016/sep/09/theresa-may-to-end-ban-on-new-grammar-schools\" title=\"\">Theresa’s May’s decision to end the grammar school ban</a>, even though it’s silly and wrong and nobody wants it.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/education/2016/sep/09/theresa-may-to-end-ban-on-new-grammar-schools\">Theresa May to end ban on new grammar schools</a> </p> </aside>  <p><strong>Who came up with the term? </strong>It’s thought <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/davidwilletts\" title=\"\">Lord Willetts</a>, the former universities minister who strongly opposes selective schooling, invented it in a 2005 speech about the dangers of mindless traditionalism. Back then, he compared it to “a man trying to repair a broken cobweb with his own hands”.</p> <p><strong>And grammar schools represent bring-backery? </strong>Absolutely. For all of May’s talk about social mobility, it’s a deliberately retrograde policy rooted in the mistaken belief that things were better in the past.</p> <p><strong>They were, though, weren’t they? We had Postman Pat back then, and </strong><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Starburst_(confectionery)\" title=\"\"><strong>Opal Fruits</strong></a><strong>. </strong>Oh, do be quiet you moronic nostalgia-obsessed nimrod. Nothing was better in the past. It was different, that’s all. Things were bad then, and things are bad now. They’re just different types of bad, is all.</p> <p><strong>Who else has used the phrase?</strong> In 2007, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/davidcameron\" title=\"\">David Cameron</a> referenced it during another row about grammar schools, saying: “In many ways, ‘bring back grammars’ is a meaningless slogan … It is a classic example of fighting a battle of the past rather than meeting the challenges of the future.”</p> <p><strong>Ah, Cameron. I miss him. </strong>No you don’t, you backwards-looking moron. He was terrible.</p> <p><strong>Is bring-backery exclusively about grammar schools, then?</strong> Nope. Look at that ridiculous campaign to <a href=\"https://www.thesun.co.uk/news/1537388/its-time-to-bring-back-the-famous-dark-blue-uk-passport-as-a-symbol-of-our-independence-after-brexit/\" title=\"\">make British passports blue again</a>. That is out-and-out bring-backery.</p> <p><strong>Right, so it’s what you say when someone attempts to resurrect an idea that died for good reason long ago? </strong>That’s right.</p> <p><strong>So when people want to ban metric measurements? </strong>Bring-backery!</p> <p><strong>And when they gripe about political correctness? </strong>They’re basically saying: “Bring back me getting away with being rude to brown folk.”</p> <p><strong>Wait, isn’t “bring-backery” just a facile term designed to shut down arguments with people you disagree with, instead of solving them in open debate like adults? </strong>Shut up, you ridiculous bring-backer.</p> <p><strong>Do say: </strong>“Don’t solve today’s problems with yesterday’s failed solutions.”</p> <p><strong>Don’t say: </strong>“Bring back bringing back bring-backery.”</p>","newspaperPageNumber":"3","wordcount":"386","commentCloseDate":"2016-09-14T16:00:04Z","commentable":"true","creationDate":"2016-09-09T11:17:34Z","firstPublicationDate":"2016-09-11T16:00:04Z","internalComposerCode":"57d29a4ee4b013613fffb952","internalOctopusCode":"11886997","internalPageCode":"2703759","isInappropriateForSponsorship":"false","isPremoderated":"false","lastModified":"2016-09-15T13:32:30Z","newspaperEditionDate":"2016-09-12T00:00:00Z","productionOffice":"UK","publication":"The Guardian","shortUrl":"https://gu.com/p/529n6","shouldH