"standfirst":"<p>Russian scientists think they may have received a signal from a star 94.4 light years from Earth. Other expert alien-spotters have moved quickly to investigate<br></p>","trailText":"Russian scientists think they may have received a signal from a star 94.4 light years from Earth. Other expert alien-spotters have moved quickly to investigate<br>","main":"<figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"a659dec5ea5ee09a4432196f426eccfc497d1e8d\"> <img src=\"https://media.guim.co.uk/a659dec5ea5ee09a4432196f426eccfc497d1e8d/0_301_4800_2879/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Is there anybody out there? … The constellation of Hercules.\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Is there anybody out there? … The constellation of Hercules.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Alamy Stock Photo</span> </figcaption> </figure>","body":"<p><strong>Name:</strong> HD164595.</p> <p><strong>Age: </strong>4.5 billion years, give or take.</p> <p><strong>Appearance: </strong>Not visible to the naked eye.</p> <p><strong>Sounds like you don’t know too much about it. </strong>That’s because it hasn’t been up to much until now.</p> <p><strong>What exactly are we talking about? </strong>A sun-sized star 94.4 light years from Earth, in the constellation of Hercules.</p> <p><strong>How interesting can it be if no one has bothered to give it a proper name? </strong>Well, it has an apparent magnitude of 7.075, a similar mass and temperature to our own sun, and a Neptune-sized planet, HD164595 b, in its orbit.</p> <p><strong>Whoop de doo.</strong> And someone from out that way may be trying to get in touch.</p> <p><strong>What are you talking about? </strong>In May 2015, a strong radio signal coming from the vicinity of HD164595 <a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/science/2016/aug/29/russian-radio-telescope-strong-signal-hd164595-seti\">was detected at the Ratan-600 observatory in Russia</a>.</p> <p><strong>Why are we only hearing about it now? </strong>Because it is due to be made public in a forthcoming presentation, leading to speculation that the signal could be coming from a transmitter built by a Type I civilisation.</p> <p><strong>You mean ET phoned from home? </strong>Maybe.</p> <p><strong>Really? </strong>No.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-embed element--supporting\" data-alt=\"Video explaining possible alien signal.\">  <iframe src=\"https://www.facebook.com/plugins/video.php?href=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.facebook.com%2Ftheguardian%2Fvideos%2F556071397913961%2F&amp;show_text=0&amp;width=400&amp;height=400\" style=\"max-width:400px;max-height:400px\" allowtransparency=\"true\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"400\" width=\"400\"></iframe> </figure>  <p><strong>Stop toying with me! </strong>While it is conceivable the signal was sent by aliens, scientists from the Search for Extraterrestrial Intelligence (Seti) <a href=\"https://setiathome.berkeley.edu/forum_thread.php?id=80193\">remain sceptical</a>.</p> <p><strong>That’s their job, I suppose. </strong>No one has been able to replicate the findings so far, even though many of the world’s telescopes have been trained on the vicinity in the last few days.</p> <p><strong>Absence of evidence isn’t evidence of absence. </strong>No, but a one-off signal is more consistent with something such as a stellar flare, or radio interference here on Earth.</p> <p><strong>You just have to believe, otherwise ET won’t call back. </strong>And even if aliens were pointing the signal directly at us, the transmitting power required would equal the total energy consumption of all humankind.</p> <p><strong>So it’s possible. </strong>But there is no reason to think they even know we’re here.</p> <p><strong>They can see our TV! They’ll be wanting Seinfeld explained to them! </strong>HD164595 is 94 light years away. None of our TV has reached there yet.</p> <p><strong>Thanks for ruining this for me. </strong>Any time.</p> <p><strong>Do say:</strong> “HELLO FROM PLANET EARTH. NO NEED TO REPLY IF YOU’RE SLIMY.”</p> <p><strong>Don’t say:</strong> “SPOILER ALERT: CHANDLER AND MONICA EVENTUALLY GET IT TOGETHER.”</p>","newspaperPageNumber":"3","wordcount":"393","commentCloseDate":"2016-09-03T11:30:00Z","commentable":"true","creationDate":"2016-08-31T11:00:22Z","firstPublicationDate":"2016-08-31T11:35:20Z","internalComposerCode":"57c6b8c6e4b0f6cb856289d4","internalOctopusCode":"11859218","internalPageCode":"2691882","isInappropriateForSponsorship":"false","isPremoderated":"false","lastModified":"2016-09-01T17:39:29Z","newspaperEditionDate":"2016-09-01T00:00:00Z","productionOffice":"UK","publication":"The Guardian","shortUrl":"https://gu.com/p/5xkf9","shouldHideAdverts":"false","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"https://media.guim.co.uk/a659dec5ea5ee09a4432196f426eccfc497d1e8d/0_301_4800_2879/500.jpg","legallySensitive":"false","lang":"en","internalRevision":"107","internalShortId":"/p/5xkf9"},"tags":[{"id":"science/alien-life","type":"keyword","sectionId":"science","sectionName":"Science","webTitle":"Alien life","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/science/alien-life","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/science/alien-life","references":[]},{"id":"science/astronomy","type":"keyword","sectionId":"science","sectionName":"Science","webTitle":"Astronomy","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/science/astronomy","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/science/astronomy","references":[]},{"id":"science/space","type":"keyword","sectionId":"science","sectionName":"Science","webTitle":"Space","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/science/space","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/science/space","references":[]},{"id":"science/science","type":"keyword","sectionId":"science","sectionName":"Science","webTitle":"Science","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/science/science","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/science/science","references":[]},{"id":"news/series/pass